<p class="note">The Spaniards call Ensaladilla any small dish with mayonnaise. The inspiration came from Ensalada Rusa. Personally, I love this recipe served on slices of warm bread as an appetizer.</p>

<h3>Ingredients</h3>

<ul>
	<li>Few leaves of lettuce (Red Leaf suggested)</li>
	<li>2 spring onions</li>
	<li>Roasted pimientos</li>
	<li>5 anchovies</li>
	<li>1 lemon</li>
	<li>1 can of tuna</li>
	<li>Pepper</li>
	<li>Mayonnaise</li>
	<li>Bread</li>
</ul>

<h3>Directions</h3>

<ol>
	<li>Chop 2 (or more as you like) spring onions</li>
	<li>Chop roasted pimientos as rectangular strips</li>
	<li>Dice 5 anchovies into small pieces (optional, but trust me it goes perfect!)</li>
	<li>Wash a few leaves of lettuce</li>
	<li>Squeeze all the juice out of a lemon into a cup</li>
	<li>Open 1 can of tuna with the lid still attached (keeps the tuna from falling out) and pour out all the water</li>
	<li>In a bowl add some mayonnaise, add the tuna, lemon juice, spring onions, and anchovies and mix well</li>
	<li>On a plate, place the few pieces of lettuce</li>
	<li>On the same plate add the dip mix</li>
	<li>Place the strips of roasted pimientos on top</li>
	<li>Now you can serve like that in a plate/bowl</li>
	<li>Or take slices of warm baguette bread and place a piece of lettuce with the mix on top</li>
</ol>
